Here is the code for a Java function that checks if a given string is a palindrome:

```
public static boolean isPalindrome(String str) {
    int left = 0;
    int right = str.length() - 1;

    while (left < right) {
        if (str.charAt(left) != str.charAt(right)) {
            return false;
        }
        left++;
        right--;
    }

    return true;
}
```

Explanation:

This function takes a string input and returns a boolean value indicating whether the string is a palindrome or not.

The function uses two pointers, `left` and `right`, to compare characters from the beginning and end of the string, respectively. It starts by setting `left` to the first character of the string and `right` to the last character of the string.

Then, it enters a loop that continues as long as `left` is less than `right`. In each iteration, it checks if the character at `left` is equal to the character at `right`. If they are not equal, the function returns `false` immediately, indicating that the string is not a palindrome. If they are equal, the function increments `left` and decrements `right` in preparation for the next iteration.

If the loop completes (i.e., `left` is no longer less than `right`), the function returns `true`, indicating that the string is a palindrome.

This implementation has a time complexity of O(n/2), which simplifies to O(n), since it only needs to loop through half of the string. Thus, it is a highly efficient solution for checking whether a string is a palindrome.

